# {{ .name }}

An Intropy **loader block**: subscribes to the `{{ .subscribesTopic }}` topic and loads each event
into the `{{ .targetSystem }}` external system through the `{{ .connector }}` connector. How the
target is reached (the transport) is chosen later, at `intropy system create`.

This scaffold is **complete and runnable on its own** — no other components and no shared
infrastructure required.

## Run it standalone

```bash
task run          # dapr run with in-memory pub/sub + a localstorage connector binding
```

Then, from another terminal, drive it end-to-end:

```bash
task publish      # publishes local/sample-data/sample-message.json onto the subscribed topic
ls local/storage/outbound   # the loaded file the connector wrote
```

Standalone, the connector defaults to a **local file binding** (`bindings.localstorage`) writing to
`./local/storage/outbound`, and pub/sub is **in-memory** — both live in `local/dapr-components/`.

## Run it as part of a system

The same component runs unchanged inside a system; the SystemHost swaps the Dapr components folder at
run time so `pubsub` becomes Redis and `binding.{{ .connector }}` becomes the connector's real
transport. Scaffold the other components next to this folder, then from the parent directory:

```bash
intropy system create -n <system-name>
dotnet run --project <SystemName>.SystemHost -- check   # validate the topology
dotnet run --project <SystemName>.SystemHost            # run the whole system locally
```

This component's edge intent (block kind, subscribed topic, connector) is recorded in
`.intropy/scaffold.json`, which `intropy system create` reads to wire the SystemHost.
